WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.120
I'm Winston Chang, I'm a software engineer at Posit, and earlier this year I did some

00:00:12.120 --> 00:00:18.920
work on a package called ChatStream, which you can use to help build AI chat applications

00:00:18.920 --> 00:00:20.760
with Shiny for Python.

00:00:20.760 --> 00:00:24.680
And it just sort of looks like this, if you can't read this it's fine, it's just basically

00:00:24.680 --> 00:00:27.879
a chat interface, you ask it a question and it gives you an answer, it talks to the open

00:00:27.879 --> 00:00:34.360
AI API, and that gives you an answer and you can have a conversation with it.

00:00:34.360 --> 00:00:38.040
And when I was working on this I showed this to the team and we were trying to figure out

00:00:38.040 --> 00:00:40.720
some fun demos to do with it.

00:00:40.720 --> 00:00:44.360
And Joe Chang had the idea like, well, what if you have it play the game 20 questions,

00:00:44.360 --> 00:00:48.360
what if you have two of these on a page, one of them thinks of an object and the other

00:00:48.360 --> 00:00:49.880
one tries to guess what that object is.

00:00:49.880 --> 00:00:55.240
So I went and I figured out how to wire up these two instances of this Shiny module to

00:00:55.240 --> 00:00:58.840
talk to each other, take the outputs from one of them and use it for the inputs of

00:00:58.840 --> 00:01:00.799
the other and vice versa.

00:01:00.799 --> 00:01:03.639
And so, again, this is going to be really small, I didn't realize this room was going

00:01:03.639 --> 00:01:06.720
to be like this, but you don't have to read this, it's not that important.

00:01:06.720 --> 00:01:14.480
This is two of these modules talking to each other playing the game of 20 questions.

00:01:14.480 --> 00:01:19.599
Now we've shown this elsewhere, and I was thinking today, for today I want to do something

00:01:19.599 --> 00:01:22.220
a little bit different.

00:01:22.220 --> 00:01:25.459
So I was thinking, like, how can we make this better?

00:01:25.459 --> 00:01:29.860
And I thought, well, you know what might be fun is if they're doing, instead of playing

00:01:29.860 --> 00:01:34.339
20 questions, you have these two chatbots doing a debate about a topic.

00:01:34.339 --> 00:01:38.980
So I went and I changed the application a little bit, I don't know if the cursor will

00:01:38.980 --> 00:01:39.980
show up there.

00:01:39.980 --> 00:01:44.300
Anyway, on the top, you can enter in your topic, there's these two chatbots.

00:01:44.300 --> 00:01:48.980
So here they're debating, you know, LLMs have subjective experience versus they don't

00:01:48.980 --> 00:01:55.099
have subjective experience, if you're a philosophy of mind person, you'll know what this all

00:01:55.099 --> 00:01:56.099
means.

00:01:56.099 --> 00:01:59.419
And then they have this debate about it, and you can, you know, you read this, and actually

00:01:59.419 --> 00:02:04.739
it's kind of interesting to engage with an argument this way, to learn about something

00:02:04.739 --> 00:02:06.940
by reading it this way.

00:02:06.940 --> 00:02:11.339
But I still thought, you know, it was a little bit dull to have these two AI chatbots doing

00:02:11.339 --> 00:02:12.380
it.

00:02:12.380 --> 00:02:16.059
So I thought, you know, how can I make this, how can I make that better, how can I make

00:02:16.059 --> 00:02:17.059
it more interesting?

00:02:17.139 --> 00:02:25.059
And I realized this could be like a Socratic dialogue, where you have characters that are

00:02:25.059 --> 00:02:26.940
doing this argument, right?

00:02:26.940 --> 00:02:32.139
So in a Socratic dialogue, just to remind everyone, you have these characters, so here

00:02:32.139 --> 00:02:38.580
we have Protagoras and Socrates here, and they might be debating something like, you

00:02:38.580 --> 00:02:42.059
know, the nature of virtue ethics, what does it mean to live a good life?

00:02:42.059 --> 00:02:47.500
So I went and I updated my application a little bit, and I added a field where you

00:02:47.500 --> 00:02:51.500
can type in, you can also add in the character that you want to embody, like one of these

00:02:51.500 --> 00:02:52.660
AI chatbots.

00:02:52.660 --> 00:02:56.899
So there's character and topic, and this is, you know, Protagoras and Socrates arguing

00:02:56.899 --> 00:02:59.860
about virtue ethics.

00:02:59.860 --> 00:03:02.860
So this was, you know, the results from this were really fun and interesting.

00:03:02.860 --> 00:03:07.220
It's a little bit more compelling reading it coming from a character, rather than just

00:03:07.220 --> 00:03:12.020
a generic chatbot.

00:03:12.020 --> 00:03:15.259
And some of the results were, I mean, it is interesting, and some of them, you know, some

00:03:15.259 --> 00:03:22.179
of the output was, like, also rhetorically very impressive.

00:03:22.179 --> 00:03:24.619
And I was thinking to myself, like, well, that's cool.

00:03:24.619 --> 00:03:27.539
How can I, you know, how can I make this even more interesting?

00:03:27.539 --> 00:03:32.259
So I picked a topic that I thought wasn't, I think will resonate with everyone here,

00:03:32.259 --> 00:03:35.300
and some characters I think everyone will be familiar with.

00:03:35.300 --> 00:03:42.979
And I had it generate some dialogue, and then I thought, okay, it would be even better

00:03:42.979 --> 00:03:45.160
if this were a song.

00:03:45.160 --> 00:03:48.740
So I went, and I didn't edit the app to generate songs, because that's, like, way beyond what

00:03:48.740 --> 00:03:55.660
I'm capable of doing, but I found someone on the internet who makes songs using AI-generated

00:03:55.660 --> 00:04:02.100
voices, which is really cool and also a little bit creepy that they can do that.

00:04:02.100 --> 00:04:04.100
But anyway, I'd like to play for you the song.

